In this speech given by President Obama at a DSCC Dinner in Chicago, he discusses the progress made during his time in office, including job creation, lower unemployment rates, increased housing values, and improved stock market performance. He also mentions the challenges faced by the American people, such as stagnant wages and increasing costs. The President criticizes the Republican-controlled Congress for not prioritizing issues that have majority support, such as immigration reform, minimum wage increase, and equal pay for equal work. He emphasizes the need for a Democratic Senate and House to advance the values and policies that he believes in. The President also acknowledges the structural disadvantages faced by Democrats in elections, such as gerrymandering and lower voter turnout in midterms. He concludes by urging the audience to feel a sense of urgency in the upcoming election and the importance of turning out voters to support Democratic candidates.